http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title.@value: Ontology for the Lipid Identification Service (LIS)

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This is is the ontology assumed by the [Lipid Identification Service (LIS)](https://github.com/marianofl1971/lis). It defines notions like experiment, hypothesis, empirical compound, theoretical compound, etc. The examples in JSON have been validated using [JSONLint](https://jsonlint.com/), and the examples in JSON-LD, using [JSON-LD Playground](https://json-ld.org/playground/).

Explanation of the execution of an adduct relation rule. Below is presented an example of adduct relation rule explanation in JSON (assuming a [particular context](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld)):
~~~~
  {
      "coreInformation":"The empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 is expected to be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+Na, because, for example, 
                            the empirical compound 495.3352@19.4689 with adduct M+H may be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) as well."
  }

~~~~
and here, an example in JSON-LD:
~~~~
{
   "@context":
"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld",
    "@type":"https://w3id.org/def/lis#ARRExplanation",
 
      "coreInformation":"The empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 is expected to be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+Na, because, for example, 
                            the empirical compound 495.3352@19.4689 with adduct M+H may be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) as well."
}
~~~~

A certainty level assignment with explanations relates an hypothesis with a certainty level and with an explanation. That is, it is a reification of a ternary relation. Below is presented an example of certaintly level assignment with explanations in JSON (assuming a [particular context](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld)):
~~~~
{
    "ruleType":"ionization_rule_type",
    "trueValue":"expected",
    "hypothesis": {
      "identifier":315,
      "empiricalCompound": {"mass":517.3172, "rt":19.4689},
      "theoreticalCompound": {"identifier":2628, "name":"PC(O-14:0/2:0)"},
      "adduct":"M+Na"
    },
    "explanation": {
      "coreInformation":"The empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 (in an experiment with positive ionization and modifier NH3) is expected to be the theoretical 
                            compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+Na, which belongs to the hierarchy GP, GP01, GP0102",
      "additionalInformation":"The empirical compound 495.3352@19.4689 is expected to be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+H, because, for example, 
                                  the empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 with adduct M+Na may be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) as well."
    }
}
~~~~
and here, an example in JSON-LD:
~~~~
{
    "@context": "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld",
    "@type": "https://w3id.org/def/lis#CLAwithExplanations",
      "ruleType":"ionization_rule_type",
    "trueValue":"expected",
    "hypothesis": {
      "identifier":315,
      "empiricalCompound": {"mass":517.3172, "rt":19.4689},
      "theoreticalCompound": {"identifier":2628, "name":"PC(O-14:0/2:0)"},
      "adduct":"M+Na"
    },
    "explanation": {
      "coreInformation":"The empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 (in an experiment with positive ionization and modifier NH3) is expected to be the theoretical 
                            compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+Na, which belongs to the hierarchy GP, GP01, GP0102",
      "additionalInformation":"The empirical compound 495.3352@19.4689 is expected to be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+H, because, for example, 
                                  the empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 with adduct M+Na may be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) as well."
    }
}

~~~~
LIS returns an array of certainty level assignments with explanations.
The certainty levels can be _impossible_, _improbable_, _possible_, _expected_ or _sure_.

An empirical compound is characterised by a mass and a retention time. Below is presented an example of empirical compound in JSON (assuming a [particular context](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld)):
~~~~
{
   "mass": 425.3504,
   "retentionTime": 19.5463
}
~~~~
and here, an example in JSON-LD:
~~~~
{
   "@context": "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld",
    "@type": "https://w3id.org/def/lis#EmpiricalCompound",
    "mass": 425.3504,
    "retentionTime": 19.5463
}
~~~~

Text describing a reasoning process. Every explanation has a core information that, depending on the rule that has been fired, can be extended with more information. Below is presented an example of explanation in JSON (assuming a [particular context](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld)):
~~~~
{
      "coreInformation":"The empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 (in an experiment with positive ionization and modifier NH3) is expected to be the theoretical 
                            compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+Na, which belongs to the hierarchy GP, GP01, GP0102",
      "additionalInformation":"The empirical compound 495.3352@19.4689 is expected to be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+H, because, for example, 
                                  the empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 with adduct M+Na may be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) as well."
    }
~~~~
and here, an example in JSON-LD:
~~~~
{
   "@context":
"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld",
   "@type":"https://w3id.org/def/lis#Explanation",
   
      "coreInformation":"The empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 (in an experiment with positive ionization and modifier NH3) is expected to be the theoretical 
                            compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+Na, which belongs to the hierarchy GP, GP01, GP0102",
      "additionalInformation":"The empirical compound 495.3352@19.4689 is expected to be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+H, because, for example, 
                                  the empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 with adduct M+Na may be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) as well."
}
~~~~

Explanation of a ionization rule. If the same conclusion is attained through an adduct relation rule, additional information explaining this fact is added to the core information. Below is presented an example of ionization rule explanation in JSON (assuming a [particular context](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld)):
~~~~
{
      "coreInformation":"The empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 (in an experiment with positive ionization and modifier NH3) is expected to be the theoretical compound 
                            PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+Na, which belongs to the hierarchy GP, GP01, GP0102",
      "additionalInformation":"The empirical compound 495.3352@19.4689 is expected to be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+H, because, for example, 
                                  the empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 with adduct M+Na may be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) as well."
}
~~~~
and here, an example in JSON-LD:
~~~~
{
   "@context":
"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld",
   "@type":"https://w3id.org/def/lis#IRExplanation",

      "coreInformation":"The empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 (in an experiment with positive ionization and modifier NH3) is expected to be the theoretical 
                            compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+Na, which belongs to the hierarchy GP, GP01, GP0102",
      "additionalInformation":"The empirical compound 495.3352@19.4689 is expected to be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+H, because, for example, 
                                  the empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 with adduct M+Na may be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) as well."
}
~~~~
It can be positive or negative.

Explanation of the execution of a retention time rule. It can contain evidence for, evidence against or both. Below is presented an example of retention time rule explanation in JSON (assuming a [particular context](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld)):
~~~~
    {
      "coreInformation":"It is possible that the empirical compound 282.2563@31.2616 is the theoretical compound 10Z-Hexadecenyl acetate with adduct M+H. The 
                            theoretical compound is a _WE_OPENPAR_ lipid with 18 carbons and one double bond",
      "evidenceFor":"For example, the compound 280.2402@28.2695 may be the theoretical compound 10E,12E-Hexadecadienyl acetate with adduct M+H, another _WE_OPENPAR_ 
                        lipid with 18 carbons and 2 double bonds.",
      "evidenceAgainst":"For example, the compound 280.2402@28.2695 may be the theoretical compound 11-Hexadecynyl acetate with adduct M+H, another _WE_OPENPAR_ lipid 
                            with 18 carbons and no double bond."
  }
~~~~
and here, an example in JSON-LD:
~~~~
{
   "@context":
"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld",
   "@type":"https://w3id.org/def/lis#RTRExplanation",
  
      "coreInformation":"It is possible that the empirical compound 282.2563@31.2616 is the theoretical compound 10Z-Hexadecenyl acetate with adduct M+H. The 
                            theoretical compound is a _WE_OPENPAR_ lipid with 18 carbons and one double bond",
      "evidenceFor":"For example, the compound 280.2402@28.2695 may be the theoretical compound 10E,12E-Hexadecadienyl acetate with adduct M+H, another _WE_OPENPAR_ 
                        lipid with 18 carbons and 2 double bonds.",
      "evidenceAgainst":"For example, the compound 280.2402@28.2695 may be the theoretical compound 11-Hexadecynyl acetate with adduct M+H, another _WE_OPENPAR_ lipid
                            with 18 carbons and no double bond."
}
~~~~
The rule types are ionization, adduct relation and retention time.

A theoretical compound has a name and an identifier. Below is presented an example of theoretical compound in JSON (assuming a [particular context](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld)):
~~~~
{
    "identifier": 32675,
    "name": "L-palmitoylcarnitine"
}
~~~~
and here, an example in JSON-LD:
~~~~
{
    "@context": "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld",
    "@type": "https://w3id.org/def/lis#TheoreticalCompound",
    "identifier": 32675,
    "name": "L-palmitoylcarnitine"
}
~~~~
Each fact instantiating this property relates an explanation of ionization rule to its additional information.
Each fact instantiating this property relates an entity (e.g. a hypothesis) with a string representing a compound playing the role of adduct.
The type of rule adduct relation.
Each fact instantiating this property relates an explanation to its core information.
Each fact instantiating this property relates a retention time rule explanation to an evidence against.
Each fact instantiating this property relates a retention time rule explanation to an evidence for.
The certainty level expected.
Each fact instantiating this property relates an explanation with a string.
It relates certainty assignments with explanations to certainty levels.
It is the relation between entities (e.g. hypotheses) and empirical compounds.
It relates entities (e.g. certainty level assignments with explanations) to explanations.
It is the relation between entities (e.g. experiments or certainty level assignments with explanations) and hypotheses.
It relates experiments with ionization modes.
It relates experiments with modifieres.
It relates explanations to rule types.
It is the relation between entities (e.g. hypotheses) and theoretical compounds.

The certainty level improbable.
